{"title_page": "Tuzluk\u00e7u", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|settlement_type = District\n|subdivision_type = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name = {{TUR}}\n|timezone= [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n|utc_offset=+2\n|image_map= Konya districts.png\n|map_caption =Location of Tuzluk\u00e7u within Turkey.\n|timezone_DST=[[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST=+3\n|official_name = Tuzluk\u00e7u\n|image_skyline =\n|image_caption =\n|image_blank_emblem =\n|blank_emblem_type =\n|map cap = Location in [[Turkey]]\n|subdivision_type2=[[Provinces of Turkey|Province]]\n|subdivision_name2 = Konya\n| area_footnotes          = {{Turkey district areas|SOURCE}}\n| area_blank1_title       = District\n| area_blank1_km2         = {{Turkey district areas|Konya|Tuzluk\u00e7u}}\n| population_footnotes    = {{Turkey district populations|SOURCE|Konya}}\n| population_urban        = {{Turkey district populations|Konya|Tuzluk\u00e7u|\u015fehir}}\n| population_as_of        = {{Turkey district populations|YEAR}}\n| population_blank1_title = District\n| population_blank1       = {{Turkey district populations|Konya|Tuzluk\u00e7u|toplam}}\n| population_density_blank1_km2  = auto\n| pushpin_map             = Turkey\n|coordinates             = {{coord|38|29|N|31|38|E|region:TR|display=inline}}\n|elevation_m = 1002\n|postal_code_type=[[Postal code]]\n|postal_code = 42xxx\n|area_code = 0332\n|blank_info = 42|blank_name=[[Turkish car number plates|Licence&nbsp;plate]]\n|leader_title= Mayor\n|leader_name = Nurettin Akbu\u011fa ([[Republican People's Party (Turkey)|CHP]])\n|website = [http://www.tuzlukcu.gov.tr/ www.tuzlukcu.gov.tr]\n}}\n\n'''Tuzluk\u00e7u''' is a town and [[Districts of Turkey|district]] of [[Konya Province]] in the [[Central Anatolia Region, Turkey|Central Anatolia]] region of [[Turkey]]. According to 2000 census, population of the district is 9,783 of which 5,845 live in the town of Tuzluk\u00e7u.<ref name=\"die\">{{cite web|url=http://www.die.gov.tr/nufus_sayimi/2000tablo5.xls|title=Census 2000, Key statistics for urban areas of Turkey|access-date=2008-03-25|author=[[Turkish Statistical Institute]]|format=XLS|language=Turkish|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5QWEsWFnQ?url=http://www.die.gov.tr/nufus_sayimi/2000tablo5.xls|archive-date=2007-07-22|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.fallingrain.com/world/TU/0/Tuzlukcu.html|title=Geographical information on Tuzluk\u00e7u, Turkey|accessdate=2008-03-25|author=Falling Rain Genomics, Inc}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tuzlukcu.gov.tr/ District governor's official website] {{in lang|tr}}\n* [http://www.tuzlukcu.bel.tr/ District municipality's official website] {{in lang|tr}}\n\n{{Districts of Turkey|provname=Konya}}\n\n{{coord|38|28|40|N|31|37|35|E|display=title|region:TR_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tuzlukcu}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Konya Province]]\n[[Category:Districts of Konya Province]]\n\n\n{{Konya-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|settlement_type = District\n|subdivision_type = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name = {{TUR}}\n|timezone= [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n|utc_offset=+2\n|image_map= Konya districts.png\n|map_caption =Location of Tuzluk\u00e7u within Turkey.\n|timezone_DST=[[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST=+3\n|official_name = Tuzluk\u00e7u\n|image_skyline =\n|image_caption =\n|image_blank_emblem =\n|blank_emblem_type =\n|map cap = Location in [[Turkey]]\n|subdivision_type2=[[Provinces of Turkey|Province]]\n|subdivision_name2 = Konya\n| area_footnotes          = {{Turkey district areas|SOURCE}}\n| area_blank1_title       = District\n| area_blank1_km2         = {{Turkey district areas|Konya|Tuzluk\u00e7u}}\n| population_footnotes    = {{Turkey district populations|SOURCE|Konya}}\n| population_urban        = {{Turkey district populations|Konya|Tuzluk\u00e7u|\u015fehir}}\n| population_as_of        = {{Turkey district populations|YEAR}}\n| population_blank1_title = District\n| population_blank1       = {{Turkey district populations|Konya|Tuzluk\u00e7u|toplam}}\n| population_density_blank1_km2  = auto\n| pushpin_map             = Turkey\n|coordinates             = {{coord|38|29|N|31|38|E|region:TR|display=inline}}\n|elevation_m = 1002\n|postal_code_type=[[Postal code]]\n|postal_code = 42xxx\n|area_code = 0332\n|blank_info = 42|blank_name=[[Turkish car number plates|Licence&nbsp;plate]]\n|leader_title= Mayor\n|leader_name = Mustafa Sak ([[Republican People's Party (Turkey)|CHP]])\n|website = [http://www.tuzlukcu.gov.tr/ www.tuzlukcu.gov.tr]\n}}\n\n'''Tuzluk\u00e7u''' is a town and [[Districts of Turkey|district]] of [[Konya Province]] in the [[Central Anatolia Region, Turkey|Central Anatolia]] region of [[Turkey]]. According to 2000 census, population of the district is 9,783 of which 5,845 live in the town of Tuzluk\u00e7u.<ref name=\"die\">{{cite web|url=http://www.die.gov.tr/nufus_sayimi/2000tablo5.xls|title=Census 2000, Key statistics for urban areas of Turkey|access-date=2008-03-25|author=[[Turkish Statistical Institute]]|format=XLS|language=Turkish|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5QWEsWFnQ?url=http://www.die.gov.tr/nufus_sayimi/2000tablo5.xls|archive-date=2007-07-22|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.fallingrain.com/world/TU/0/Tuzlukcu.html|title=Geographical information on Tuzluk\u00e7u, Turkey|accessdate=2008-03-25|author=Falling Rain Genomics, Inc}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.tuzlukcu.gov.tr/ District governor's official website] {{in lang|tr}}\n* [http://www.tuzlukcu.bel.tr/ District municipality's official website] {{in lang|tr}}\n\n{{Districts of Turkey|provname=Konya}}\n\n{{coord|38|28|40|N|31|37|35|E|display=title|region:TR_type:city_source:GNS-enwiki}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tuzlukcu}}\n[[Category:Populated places in Konya Province]]\n[[Category:Districts of Konya Province]]\n\n\n{{Konya-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Cemyildiz", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tuzluk%C3%A7u"}
{"title_page": "Teachers Without Borders", "text_new": "[[File:TWB Logo Blue SQUARE.png|thumbnail|right]]\n'''Teachers Without Borders''' (''TWB'') is an international organization launched in 2000 with a mission to connect teachers to information and each other in order to close the education divide and based upon the premise that teachers are community change agents and key catalysts of global development priorities. The organization was founded by [https://teacherswithoutborders.org/founder/ Dr. Fred Mednick], a former principal.\n\n==Accomplishments==\nTeachers Without Borders received the '''[https://luxembourgpeaceprize.org/laureates/outstanding-peace-education/2018-teachers-without-borders/ 2018 Luxembourg Peace Prize]''' for Outstanding Peace Education, recognized for a free Peace Education program involving teachers from regions in conflict, for having embedded peace education into all TWB courses (see below), and its Voice of Teachers Radio Show in Nigeria.\n\nTeachers Without Borders received the [https://www.changemakers.com/champions-quality-education-africa '''Champions of African Education Award'''] (2010) for its use of radio and local educational capacity building to disseminate information about the United Nations Millennium Development Goals. In 2018, TWB's membership has reached 177 countries. Teachers Without Borders membership is free and enables local educators the opportunity to connect with colleagues globally.\n\nTeachers Without Borders also received the '''[http://peacesymposium.org.uk/the-ahmadiyya-muslim-peace-prize Ahmadiyya Muslim Peace Prize]''' for \"outstanding work in the promotion of peace through efforts to convene teachers from regions in conflict, provide unfettered access to courses and networks devoted to teacher professional development, and to ensure that peace education is integrated into all initiatives. The formal announcement can be viewed [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=viaSBMQxcAk&t=9s '''here'''].\n\n==Approach==\nTeachers Without Borders claims that teachers represent the largest professional community in the world (over 65 million); that teachers are uniquely suited as local leaders to recognize and help address development needs; that professional isolation and inconsequential or missing teacher professional development undermines social change; and that the transformation of pre-service and in-service teacher development can bring about more sustainable, equitable, democratic, and economically stable societies.\n\n==Initiatives and Courses==\nTeachers Without Borders' initiatives and courses are offered in various formats and settings: online, in schools, as community workshops, in books and journals, and on the radio. All programs have been conceived and led by Teachers Without Borders' members and partners around the world. Content of all TWB [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/allcourses/ '''courses'''] and [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/training-resources/ workshop resources] are free and governed by the least restrictive Creative Commons license.  '''Initiatives''' include: [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/eie/ education in emergencies], [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/girls-education/ girls' education], [https://web.archive.org/web/20151115081416/http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/twb-peace/ peace and human rights education], [https://teacherswithoutborders.org/bullying/ Bullying], [https://teacherswithoutborders.org/ict-in-education/ ICT in Education], and [https://teacherswithoutborders.org/child-friendly-spaces/ Child-Friendly Spaces]. as well as several teacher pre-service and in-service professional development opportunities - including a five-course Certificate of Teaching Mastery program.\n\nMost Teachers Without Borders initiatives are accompanied by [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/allcourses/ courses] offered independently, at universities such as [http://www.education.jhu.edu/faculty/SOE_Faculty/fred-mednick Johns Hopkins University's School of Education] (where TWB's founder is an Assistant Professor), and through the [https://www.canvas.net Canvas Network], an online MOOC provider.  Those courses include:  ''[http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/educating-girls/ Educating Girls]''; [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/asap-education-in-emergencies/ ASAP:  Education in Emergencies]; [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/peacecourse Peace and Human Rights]; the five course [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/ctm/ ''Certificate of Teaching Mastery'']; a course on ICTs for educators entitled:  ''[http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/high-tech-high-touch-high-teach/ High-Tech, High-Touch, High-Teach]''; and ''[http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/globaled/ Global Urban Education]''.\n\n==Flagship Programs==\n\n===Education in Emergencies===\n[[File:TWB ChinatoPakistan.jpg|thumbnail|right|TWB Disaster Risk attack]]\nThe ''[http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/eie/ Emergency Education Program]'' works with teachers on preparedness and planning to avoid crises or lessen their impacts, education amidst emergencies, and in the reconstruction phase.  Teachers Without Borders has also helped to launch Parsquake, a consortium of NGOs devoted to earthquake science and safety throughout Persian speaking countries particularly vulnerable and seismically active regions of the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://teacherswithoutborders.org/eie/|title=Emergency Education {{!}} Teachers Without Borders|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> This program was initiated after the [[2008 Sichuan earthquake|2008 earthquake]] in the [[Sichuan]] region of [[China]] and, in 2011, will engage and support teachers in Finland.The program also supports [[emergency relief]], reconstruction and recovery efforts in areas hit by [[natural disasters]], such as the [[2010 Pakistan floods|2010 floods]] in [[Pakistan]]. The online MOOC, entitled [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/asap-education-in-emergencies/ ASAP: Education in Emergencies], is available without cost.\n\n===Peace and Human Rights Education===\n[[File:Haiti Fenel wikipedia.jpg|thumbnail|right|TWB Peace sacrifice in Haiti]]\nThe [https://teacherswithoutborders.org/peace-ed/ Peace Education Initiative] helps teachers promote peace in their classrooms and communities. Content of [https://www.scribd.com/doc/40571872/COMPLETE-PROGRAM-Dr-Joseph-Hungwa-Memorial-Peace-Education-Program-Parts-1-6 TWB's Peace Program] is available without cost. The [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/peacecourse/ Peace Education course] is available to the public as a MOOC and has been offered for Continuing Education Units at Johns Hopkins University.\n\n===Girls' Education===\nTeachers Without Borders' [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/girls-education/ girls' education programs] address four central themes:  (1) access (2) education in emergencies (3) public health, and (4) empowerment. The organization addresses these four themes by connecting global educators to NGOs working in the field; offering a free and low-fee course: ([http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/educating-girls/ Educating Girls]) in partnership with Johns Hopkins University and through the Canvas Network; and by promoting a [https://web.archive.org/web/20151115080828/http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/earthquake-science-and-safety-initiative/ Girls' Quake Science and Safety Initiative] - designed [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ul2JEVIH8zs in partnership with USGS] (United States Geological Survey)  to ensure access to earthquake science education for teachers and schools in seismically-vulnerable communities around the world.\n\n===Certificate of Teaching Mastery===\nTeachers Without Borders' ''Certificate of Teaching Mastery'' helped to pioneer global access to online teacher professional development through Rice University's \"connexions\" program, and is available without cost on the Canvas course platform.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://teacherswithoutborders.org/programs/core-programs/certificate-teaching-mastery |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-11-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130091538/http://teacherswithoutborders.org/programs/core-programs/certificate-teaching-mastery |archivedate=2010-11-30 }}</ref> It consists of five courses that help teachers improve their professional knowledge, classroom practice, and leadership skills. This program has been deployed throughout [[Sub-Saharan Africa]], as well as in [[Mexico]] and [[Peru]]\n\n==Countries==\nTeachers Without Borders programs and resources have been adopted by teachers and communities in 177 countries [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/where-we-work/ worldwide], including: [[Afghanistan]], Bangladesh, [[Brazil]], [[Burundi]], [[Cameroon]], China, [[Ghana]], Haiti, [[India]], [[Kenya]], [[Mexico]], Nigeria, Pakistan, [[Rwanda]], [[South Africa]], Suriname, [[Turkey]], [[Uganda]] and the [[United States of America]].\n\n[[File:ChalkboardTWB drop (1).png|thumbnail|right]]\nOn May 15, 2017, the United States IRS automatically revoked the federal tax exemption status of Teachers Without Borders for \"failure to file a Form 990-series return or notice for three consecutive years.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.charitynavigator.org/index.cfm?bay=search.summary&orgid=12775|title=Charity Navigator - CN Advisory of Teachers Without Borders|website=Charity Navigator|language=en|access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guidestar.org/profile/91-2023723|title=Teachers Without Borders - GuideStar Profile|website=www.guidestar.org|language=en|access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, 2020, the Office of the Secretary of State of Washington State reinstated Teachers Without Borders (UBI Number 602 008 785).\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Teachers Across Borders]]\n* [https://facebook.com/teacherswithoutborders Teachers Without Borders Facebook page]\n* [https://twitter.com/teachersnetwork Teachers Without Borders Twitter]\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Facebook|teacherswithoutborders}}\n* {{Twitter|teachersnetwork}}\n* {{LinkedIn page|company/twbglobal}}\n* [https://teacherswithoutborders.org/burning/ Burning Issues Newsletter]\n* [https://flipboard.com/@fredmed TWB Magazine: The Voice of Teachers] \n* [https://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/training-resources/ Free Workshop Materials]\n* [https://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/twb-public-library/ Free TWB Library]\n\n[[Category:International educational organizations]]\n[[Category:International organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Peace organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Teacher training]]\n[[Category:Sustainable development]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:TWB Logo Blue SQUARE.png|thumbnail|right]]\n'''Teachers Without Borders''' (''TWB'') is an international organization launched in 2000 with a mission to connect teachers to information and each other in order to close the education divide and based upon the premise that teachers are community change agents and key catalysts of global development priorities. The organization was founded by [https://teacherswithoutborders.org/founder/ Dr. Fred Mednick], a former principal.  \n\n=='''Accomplishments'''==\nTeachers Without Borders received the '''[https://luxembourgpeaceprize.org/laureates/outstanding-peace-education/2018-teachers-without-borders/ 2018 Luxembourg Peace Prize]''' for Outstanding Peace Education, recognized for a free Peace Education program involving teachers from regions in conflict, for having embedded peace education into all TWB courses (see below), and its Voice of Teachers Radio Show in Nigeria.\n\nTeachers Without Borders received the [https://www.changemakers.com/champions-quality-education-africa '''Champions of African Education Award'''] (2010) for its use of radio and local educational capacity building to disseminate information about the United Nations Millennium Development Goals. In 2018, TWB's membership has reached 177 countries. Teachers Without Borders membership is free and enables local educators the opportunity to connect with colleagues globally.\n\nTeachers Without Borders also received the '''[http://peacesymposium.org.uk/the-ahmadiyya-muslim-peace-prize Ahmadiyya Muslim Peace Prize]''' for \"outstanding work in the promotion of peace through efforts to convene teachers from regions in conflict, provide unfettered access to courses and networks devoted to teacher professional development, and to ensure that peace education is integrated into all initiatives. The formal announcement can be viewed [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=viaSBMQxcAk&t=9s '''here'''].\n\n=='''Approach'''==\nTeachers Without Borders claims that teachers represent the largest professional community in the world (over 65 million); that teachers are uniquely suited as local leaders to recognize and help address development needs; that professional isolation and inconsequential or missing teacher professional development undermines social change; and that the transformation of pre-service and in-service teacher development can bring about more sustainable, equitable, democratic, and economically stable societies.\n\n=='''Initiatives and Courses'''==\nTeachers Without Borders' initiatives and courses are offered in various formats and settings: online, in schools, as community workshops, in books and journals, and on the radio. All programs have been conceived and led by Teachers Without Borders' members and partners around the world. Content of all TWB [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/allcourses/ '''courses'''] and [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/training-resources/ workshop resources] are free and governed by the least restrictive Creative Commons license.  '''Initiatives''' include: [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/eie/ education in emergencies], [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/girls-education/ girls' education], [https://web.archive.org/web/20151115081416/http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/twb-peace/ peace and human rights education], [https://teacherswithoutborders.org/bullying/ Bullying], [https://teacherswithoutborders.org/ict-in-education/ ICT in Education], and [https://teacherswithoutborders.org/child-friendly-spaces/ Child-Friendly Spaces]. as well as several teacher pre-service and in-service professional development opportunities - including a five-course Certificate of Teaching Mastery program.\n\nMost Teachers Without Borders initiatives are accompanied by [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/allcourses/ courses] offered independently, at universities such as [http://www.education.jhu.edu/faculty/SOE_Faculty/fred-mednick Johns Hopkins University's School of Education] (where TWB's founder is an Assistant Professor), and through the [https://www.canvas.net Canvas Network], an online MOOC provider.  Those courses include:  ''[http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/educating-girls/ Educating Girls]''; [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/asap-education-in-emergencies/ ASAP:  Education in Emergencies]; [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/peacecourse Peace and Human Rights]; the five course [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/ctm/ ''Certificate of Teaching Mastery'']; a course on ICTs for educators entitled:  ''[http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/high-tech-high-touch-high-teach/ High-Tech, High-Touch, High-Teach]''; and ''[http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/globaled/ Global Urban Education]''.\n\n=='''Flagship Programs'''==\n\n===Education in Emergencies===\n[[File:TWB ChinatoPakistan.jpg|thumbnail|right|TWB Disaster Risk attack]]\nThe ''[http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/eie/ Emergency Education Program]'' works with teachers on preparedness and planning to avoid crises or lessen their impacts, education amidst emergencies, and in the reconstruction phase.  Teachers Without Borders has also helped to launch Parsquake, a consortium of NGOs devoted to earthquake science and safety throughout Persian speaking countries particularly vulnerable and seismically active regions of the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://teacherswithoutborders.org/eie/|title=Emergency Education {{!}} Teachers Without Borders|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-29}}</ref> This program was initiated after the [[2008 Sichuan earthquake|2008 earthquake]] in the [[Sichuan]] region of [[China]] and, in 2011, will engage and support teachers in Finland.The program also supports [[emergency relief]], reconstruction and recovery efforts in areas hit by [[natural disasters]], such as the [[2010 Pakistan floods|2010 floods]] in [[Pakistan]]. The online MOOC, entitled [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/asap-education-in-emergencies/ ASAP: Education in Emergencies], is available without cost. \n\n===Peace and Human Rights Education===\n[[File:Haiti Fenel wikipedia.jpg|thumbnail|right|TWB Peace sacrifice in Haiti]]\nThe [https://teacherswithoutborders.org/peace-ed/ Peace Education Initiative] helps teachers promote peace in their classrooms and communities. Content of [https://www.scribd.com/doc/40571872/COMPLETE-PROGRAM-Dr-Joseph-Hungwa-Memorial-Peace-Education-Program-Parts-1-6 TWB's Peace Program] is available without cost. The [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/peacecourse/ Peace Education course] is available to the public as a MOOC and has been offered for Continuing Education Units at Johns Hopkins University.\n\n===Girls' Education===\nTeachers Without Borders' [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/girls-education/ girls' education programs] address four central themes:  (1) access (2) education in emergencies (3) public health, and (4) empowerment. The organization addresses these four themes by connecting global educators to NGOs working in the field; offering a free and low-fee course: ([http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/educating-girls/ Educating Girls]) in partnership with Johns Hopkins University and through the Canvas Network; and by promoting a [https://web.archive.org/web/20151115080828/http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/earthquake-science-and-safety-initiative/ Girls' Quake Science and Safety Initiative] - designed [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ul2JEVIH8zs in partnership with USGS] (United States Geological Survey)  to ensure access to earthquake science education for teachers and schools in seismically-vulnerable communities around the world.\n\n===Certificate of Teaching Mastery===\nTeachers Without Borders' ''Certificate of Teaching Mastery'' helped to pioneer global access to online teacher professional development through Rice University's \"connexions\" program, and is available without cost on the Canvas course platform..<ref>{{cite web |url=http://teacherswithoutborders.org/programs/core-programs/certificate-teaching-mastery |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-11-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101130091538/http://teacherswithoutborders.org/programs/core-programs/certificate-teaching-mastery |archivedate=2010-11-30 }}</ref> It consists of five courses that help teachers improve their professional knowledge, classroom practice, and leadership skills. This program has been deployed throughout [[Sub-Saharan Africa]], as well as in [[Mexico]] and [[Peru]]\n\n=='''Countries'''==\nTeachers Without Borders programs and resources have been adopted by teachers and communities in 177 countries [http://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/where-we-work/ worldwide], including: [[Afghanistan]], Bangladesh, [[Brazil]], [[Burundi]], [[Cameroon]], China, [[Ghana]], Haiti, [[India]], [[Kenya]], [[Mexico]], Nigeria, Pakistan, [[Rwanda]], [[South Africa]], Suriname, [[Turkey]], [[Uganda]] and the [[United States of America]].\n\n[[File:ChalkboardTWB drop (1).png|thumbnail|right]]\nOn May 15, 2017, the United States IRS automatically revoked the federal tax exemption status of Teachers Without Borders for \"failure to file a Form 990-series return or notice for three consecutive years.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.charitynavigator.org/index.cfm?bay=search.summary&orgid=12775|title=Charity Navigator - CN Advisory of Teachers Without Borders|website=Charity Navigator|language=en|access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guidestar.org/profile/91-2023723|title=Teachers Without Borders - GuideStar Profile|website=www.guidestar.org|language=en|access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, 2020, the Office of the Secretary of State of Washington State reinstated Teachers Without Borders (UBI Number 602 008 785). \n\n== See also ==\n* [[Teachers Across Borders]]\n* [https://facebook.com/teacherswithoutborders Teachers Without Borders Facebook page]\n* [https://twitter.com/teachersnetwork Teachers Without Borders Twitter]\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See [[Wikipedia:Footnotes]] on how to create references using <ref></ref> tags which will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Facebook|teacherswithoutborders}}\n* {{Twitter|teachersnetwork}}\n* {{LinkedIn page|company/twbglobal}}\n* [https://teacherswithoutborders.org/burning/ Burning Issues Newsletter]\n* [https://flipboard.com/@fredmed TWB Magazine: The Voice of Teachers] \n* [https://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/training-resources/ Free Workshop Materials]\n* [https://www.teacherswithoutborders.org/twb-public-library/ Free TWB Library]\n\n[[Category:International educational organizations]]\n[[Category:International organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Peace organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Teacher training]]\n[[Category:Sustainable development]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Heading with bold", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Teachers_Without_Borders"}
{"title_page": "Trump International Hotel Las Vegas", "text_new": "{{Infobox building\n| image = Trump International Hotel Las Vegas.jpg\n| caption = Trump International Hotel Las Vegas, January 2017.\n| location = [[Paradise, Nevada]], [[United States]]\n| address = 2000 Fashion Show Drive\n| coordinates = {{coord|36.1296|-115.1727|format=dms|type:landmark_region:US-NV|display=inline,title}}\n| groundbreaking_date = July 12, 2005\n| start_date = November 2005\n| architect = \n| owner = [[Phil Ruffin]], [[Trump Organization]], [[Hilton Grand Vacations]]\n| floor_area = {{convert|185,805|m2|abbr=on}}\n| parking = 550\n| building_type = [[Condo hotel]]\n| hotel_name = Trump International Hotel Las Vegas\n| logo = \n| logo_width = \n| logo_caption = \n| topped_out_date = May 25, 2007\n| opening_date = {{Start date|2008|03|31}}\n| developer = [[Trump Organization]]\n| operator = [[Trump Organization]]\n| number_of_rooms = \n| number_of_suites = 1,282\n| number_of_restaurants = 2\n| floors = 64\n| height = {{convert|622|ft}}\n| website = {{url|trumphotels.com/las-vegas}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\nThe '''Trump International Hotel Las Vegas''' is a 64-story [[Luxury real estate|luxury]] [[hotel]], [[condominium]], and [[timeshare]] located on Fashion Show Drive near [[Las Vegas Boulevard]], just off the [[Las Vegas Strip]] in [[Paradise, Nevada|Paradise]], [[Nevada]], US, named for real estate developer and the 45th and current [[President of the United States]] [[Donald Trump]]. It is located down the street from [[Wynn Las Vegas]], behind the former site of the [[New Frontier Hotel and Casino]] on {{convert|3.46|acre|m2}}, near the [[Fashion Show Mall]], and features both non-residential hotel condominiums and residential [[condominium]]s. The exterior glass is infused with gold.<ref>{{cite news |first=Michael J. |last=Mishak |title=Trump's tower a sore spot on the Strip |date=April 30, 2011 |accessdate=November 11, 2016 |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/apr/30/nation/la-na-0430-trump-vegas-20110430}}</ref>\n\nTower 1 opened on March 31, 2008, with 1,282 rooms.<ref name= apr30>{{cite news|last= Mishak|first= Michael J.|url= http://articles.latimes.com/2011/apr/30/nation/la-na-0430-trump-vegas-20110430|title= Trump's tower a sore spot on the Strip|date= April 30, 2011|newspaper= Los Angeles Times|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref> It has two restaurants: DJT, the developer's initials, and a poolside restaurant, H2(eau).<ref name=LATblog033108>Jen Leo, [https://web.archive.org/web/20080426133010/http://travel.latimes.com/daily-deal-blog/?p=1599 Las Vegas Trump Tower opens today], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', March 31, 2008.</ref>  Trump announced that a second, identical tower would be built next to the first tower, but the plan was suspended after the mid-2000s recession. It is [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas's]] tallest residential building at {{convert|622|ft}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trumplv.com/pdfs/fact_sheet.pdf|title=Fact sheet|website=Trumplv.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070703164553/http://www.trumplv.com/pdfs/fact_sheet.pdf|archivedate=2007-07-03}}</ref> In September 2012, the [[Trump Organization]] announced that it sold roughly 300 condominium units in Trump International Hotel Las Vegas to [[Hilton Worldwide]]'s timeshare division, [[Hilton Grand Vacations]].<ref>{{cite web|last= Segall|first= Eli|url= http://m.vegasinc.com/news/2012/sep/06/trump-tower-las-vegas-strip-sells-300-units-timesh/|title= Trump tower on Las Vegas Strip sells some 300 units as timeshares|date= September 6, 2012|website= Vegas Inc}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn April 2002, [[Phil Ruffin]] announced that he had partnered with Donald Trump to build Trump Tower Las Vegas, a $300 million 60-story condominium tower with 300 units and the possibility of a casino, to be constructed on Fashion Show Drive, near Ruffin's [[New Frontier Hotel and Casino]]. Trump had initially approached Ruffin two years earlier about developing a property on or near the Las Vegas Strip. Construction on Trump Tower Las Vegas was to begin in six to seven months, and was expected to last approximately 18 months.<ref>{{cite news|last= Robison|first= Jennifer|url= http://lasvegassun.com/news/2002/apr/23/trump-ruffin-in-lv-luxury-condo-deal/|title= Trump, Ruffin in LV luxury condo deal|date= April 23, 2002|newspaper= [[Las Vegas Sun]]|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref> In August 2003, Ruffin said the tower had been decreased to 43 stories and was expected to cost $272 million.<ref name=nov6>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2003/Nov-06-Thu-2003/business/22527967.html|title=Trump: Only things up in air about Las Vegas plans are where, how big|last=Simpson|first=Jeff|date=November 6, 2003|work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050131093509/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2003/Nov-06-Thu-2003/business/22527967.html|archive-date=January 31, 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2003, Trump denied that the project had been delayed or that it was suffering from a lack of financing. Trump also said he was considering \"something on a larger scale\" for the project.<ref name=nov6/><ref>{{cite news|last= Benston|first= Liz|url= http://lasvegassun.com/news/2003/nov/06/ruffin-trump-exploring-larger-vegas-condo-complex/|title= Ruffin, Trump exploring larger Vegas condo complex|date= November 6, 2003|newspaper= Las Vegas Sun|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref> In July 2004, Ruffin said the project had been delayed up to that point because of other business ventures, including Trump's reality television show, ''[[The Apprentice (U.S. TV series)|The Apprentice]]''.<ref name= july30>{{cite news|last= Shubinski|first= Jennifer|url= http://lasvegassun.com/news/2004/jul/30/trump-in-new-lv-condo-deal/|title= Trump in new LV condo deal|date= July 30, 2004|newspaper= Las Vegas Sun|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref> That month, Trump and Ruffin announced revised plans for Trump International Hotel and Tower, a $300 million condominium-hotel with over 1,000 units.<ref name= july30/> Although Trump held a Nevada gaming license, he chose not to include a casino on the property.<ref>{{cite news|last= Hirsch|first= Jerry|url= http://articles.latimes.com/2004/jul/30/business/fi-trump30|title= Trump's New Big, Big Idea: Condos on the Vegas Strip|date= July 30, 2004|newspaper= Los Angeles Times|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref> Donald Trump's son [[Eric Trump]] later said, \"We have no problem getting a gaming license, but we wanted to do something different here. We wanted a true luxury resort experience. It's hard to have a high-quality product when you walk into 'ding, ding, ding' and there are people walking around in [[Aloha shirt|Hawaiian shirts]] with big plastic drink mugs.\"<ref name=vegasinc>{{cite web|url=http://vegasinc.com/business/tourism/2013/apr/02/hired-or-fired-how-trump-doing-after-5-years/|title=Hired or fired? How the Trump is doing after five years in Las Vegas|last=Sylvester|first=Ron|date=April 2, 2013|website=VegasInc.com|access-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nRuffin appeared in an October 2004 episode of ''The Apprentice'' to sign a $300 million deal with Trump regarding the project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2004/Oct-31-Sun-2004/business/25115551.html|title=Inside Gaming: Street hints suitors souring on Rio|last=Smith|first=Rod|date=October 31, 2004|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041208192018/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2004/Oct-31-Sun-2004/business/25115551.html|archive-date=December 8, 2004}}</ref> The project was referenced again in the show's [[The Apprentice (U.S. season 2)|second-season]] finale, when winner [[Kelly Perdew]] was offered a job at the property.<ref name=april9/> [[Jack Wishna]], who introduced Trump to Ruffin, was a minority partner in the project.<ref name= apr30/><ref name= july13/> In January 2005, the project was valued at $1 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Jan-21-Fri-2005/business/25705091.html|title=Expert sees upside for high-rise condos|last=Smith|first=Hubble|date=January 21, 2005|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051212012307/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Jan-21-Fri-2005/business/25705091.html|archive-date=December 12, 2005}}</ref> Groundbreaking was initially scheduled for May 2005, with completion expected by the end of 2006.<ref name=april11/> By May 2005, all of the tower's 1,282 condominium units had been reserved by prospective buyers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/May-05-Thu-2005/business/1409613.html|title=Trump condo project reserves all 1,283 units|last=Stutz|first=Howard|date=May 5, 2005|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050507102935/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/May-05-Thu-2005/business/1409613.html|archive-date=May 7, 2005}}</ref>\n\nTrump and Ruffin held a groundbreaking ceremony for the project on July 12, 2005.<ref name= july13>{{cite news|last= Benston|first= Liz|url= http://lasvegassun.com/news/2005/jul/13/trump-the-star-of-the-show-in-condo-resort-groundb/|title= Trump the star of the show in condo resort groundbreaking|date= July 13, 2005|newspaper= Las Vegas Sun|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Jul-12-Tue-2005/business/2469393.html|title=With project's start, Trump's time has come|last=Stutz|first=Howard|date=July 12, 2005|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051118155355/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Jul-12-Tue-2005/business/2469393.html|archive-date=November 18, 2005}}</ref> The ''[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]'' wrote that the event was \"really a [[Ribbon-cutting ceremony|ribbon-cutting]] and photo opportunity\". News programs such as ''[[Access Hollywood]]'' and ''[[Extra (U.S. TV program)|Extra]]'' provided coverage of the event, which was attended by approximately 300 state and local government representatives, as well as [[Carolyn Goodman (politician)|Carolyn Goodman]], [[showgirl]]s, [[Steve Wynn]] and his wife [[Elaine Wynn]], and [[Miss USA 2005]] winner [[Chelsea Cooley]].<ref name= july13/><ref name=lvrjJul13>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Jul-13-Wed-2005/business/2484466.html|title=Living the high life, Trump style|last=Stutz|first=Howard|date=July 13, 2005|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060427032759/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Jul-13-Wed-2005/business/2484466.html|archive-date=April 27, 2006}}</ref>\n\nCondominium units went on sale the same day with the opening of a $3 million temporary sales center at the corner of South Las Vegas Boulevard and Fashion Show Drive, in front of the New Frontier. The building was {{convert|8100|sqft|abbr=on}}, and featured a 10-foot replica of the tower.<ref name= july13/><ref name=april11/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Jun-21-Tue-2005/business/2210922.html|title=Trump International Hotel groundbreaking set for July 12|last=Sutz|first=Howard|date=June 21, 2005|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060427001205/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Jun-21-Tue-2005/business/2210922.html|archive-date=April 27, 2006}}</ref> That month, an [[NBA]] team was in negotiations to purchase an entire floor of the tower, while Trump was considering an alternative version of ''The Apprentice'' that would involve the tower.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Jul-13-Wed-2005/news/26873256.html|title=Team in talks to buy Trump floor |last=Clarke|first=Norm|date=July 13, 2005|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051208014415/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Jul-13-Wed-2005/news/26873256.html|archive-date=December 8, 2005}}</ref> Construction was expected to begin by the end of that summer, and was expected to last 24 to 30 months.<ref name=lvrjJul13/>\n\nConstruction began in November 2005, when the building's foundation was poured.<ref name= may27>{{cite news|url= http://www.reviewjournal.com/real-estate/trump-celebrates-project|title= Trump celebrates project|date= May 27, 2007|newspaper = Las Vegas Review-Journal|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref> After the completion of a 36,000-square-foot recreational deck in March 2006, an average of 800 workers constructed one new floor for the tower approximately every six days.<ref name= may27/> The tower was [[topping out|topped out]] on May 25, 2007.<ref name= may27/> The project was constructed at a cost of $500 million,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2006/Oct-15-Sun-2006/business/9667092.html|title=The Next Wave|last=Stutz|first=Howard|date=October 15, 2006|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061201164752/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2006/Oct-15-Sun-2006/business/9667092.html|archive-date=December 1, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/site-work-under-way-windmill-lane-plaza|title=Site work under way for Windmill Lane Plaza|date=May 28, 2007|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|access-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref> on {{convert|3|acres|abbr=on}} of land that was part of the rear parking lot for the New Frontier.<ref name= july13/> The project was designed by [[Joel Bergman|Bergman, Walls & Associates]] and built by [[Perini Building Company]].<ref name= may27/>\n\nTrump Hotel Las Vegas opened on March 31, 2008. An opening ceremony was held by Trump and Ruffin on April 11, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://mix941fm.cbslocal.com/2011/07/05/recap-the-good-years-with-mayor-oscar-goodman/trump-international-hotel-tower-las-vegas-opening-ceremony/|title= Trump International Hotel & Tower Las Vegas - Opening Ceremony|publisher= CBS| date= July 5, 2011|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref> By October 2008, only 21 percent of condo unit sales had closed, as potential buyers had trouble securing mortgages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lvrj.com/business/30934179.html|title=Credit squeeze hits high-rises|last=Knightly|first=Arnold M.|date=October 14, 2008|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081015141654/http://www.lvrj.com/business/30934179.html|archive-date=October 15, 2008}}</ref> {{as of|2013}}, Eric Trump oversees operations at the tower.<ref name=vegasinc/>\n\nOn December 4\u20135, 2015, employees voted in favor of unionizing the hotel property. It was organized by the Bartenders Union and the [[Culinary Workers Union]] and supervised by the [[National Labor Relations Board]] (NLRB) under the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Stutz|first=Howard|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/culinary-calls-contract-talks-after-trump-workers-vote-union|title=Culinary calls for contract talks after Trump workers vote for union|date=December 7, 2015|newspaper=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]|accessdate=December 7, 2015}}</ref> Donald Trump owns a penthouse on the 61st floor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/trump-hotel-executive-uses-personalized-care-build-customer-base|title=Trump hotel executive uses personalized care to build customer base|last=|first=|date=June 30, 2008|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|access-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Second tower===\nBy April 2005, a second, identical 64-story tower was being planned.<ref name= april11>{{cite web|url= http://www.adweek.com/news/advertising/it-takes-2-gearys-sell-trump-towers-78878|last= Schmelzer|first= Randi|title= It Takes 2 Gearys to Sell Trump Towers|work= Adweek|date= April 11, 2005|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref> Sales of the second tower were planned to begin by the end of 2005, with a 35 percent increase in prices from the first tower.<ref name=lvrjJul13/> In November 2005, the second tower was planned to open sometime in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last=Benston|first= Liz|url= http://lasvegassun.com/news/2005/nov/20/north-strip-brink-of-a-boom/|title= North Strip: Brink of a boom?|date= November 20, 2005|newspaper= Las Vegas Sun|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2007, the second tower was the subject of an episode of ''The Apprentice'' in which the show's candidates were tasked with creating a marketing program for the new tower.<ref name=april9>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/tower-pitch-goes-prime-time|title=Tower Pitch Goes Prime Time|last=|first=|date=April 9, 2007|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|access-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.reviewjournal.com/real-estate/trump-announces-second-tower|title= Trump announces second tower|date= May 6, 2007|newspaper = Las Vegas Review-Journal|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref> Condo units for the tower went on sale the next day.<ref name=april9/><ref name= may27/> Trump said the tower would be nearly identical to the first tower, and would also include 1,282 units.<ref name=april9/> Because of rising construction expenses, the second tower was expected to cost $625 million, which would have brought the total cost of Trump International Hotel and Tower to $1.1 billion.<ref name=april9/> This number was later reported to be $1.2 billion in February 2008, at which point the second tower was expected to begin construction at the end of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/opening-slated-trump-condo-hotel|title=Opening slated for Trump condo-hotel|date=February 5, 2008|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|access-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2008, Trump said he had not decided on a start date for the second tower, choosing to wait until all sales had closed on the first tower's rooms. At that time, reservations were still being accepted for the second tower's units.<ref>{{cite news|last= Stutz|first= Howard|url= http://www.reviewjournal.com/inside-gaming/trumps-second-tower-may-wait|title= Trump's second tower may wait|date= April 6, 2008|newspaper= Las Vegas Review-Journal|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref> The second tower was ultimately put on hold because of bad credit markets.<ref name= August1/> In August 2015, Eric Trump spoke of the potential for the second tower: \"I think in time it's a very good possibility.\"<ref name= August1>{{cite news|last = Botkin|first= Ben|url= http://www.reviewjournal.com/politics/elections/trump-has-piece-las-vegas|title= Trump has a piece of Las Vegas|date= August 1, 2015|newspaper= Las Vegas Review-Journal|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Lobby Trump International Hotel Las Vegas (38532499500).jpg|Lobby\nFile:Lobby Trump International Hotel Las Vegas (38532498610).jpg|Entrance\nFile:Trumplvtowermarch2006.jpg|Construction in March 2006\nFile:Trump Tower Las_Vegas - August_2007.jpg|Construction photo taken in August 2007 from the Riviera Hotel and Casino.\nFile:Trump and FashionShow Las Vegas Strip.jpg|Completed first tower as seen from south of [[Wynn Las Vegas]]\nFile:Trump hotel Las Vegas 2009.jpg|Trump Hotel in 2009\nFile:Las-Vegas-Trump-Hotel-8480.jpg|Trump Hotel in 2013\nFile:Trump Hotel in Las Vegas-2017.jpg|Trump Hotel in 2017\nFile:Las Vegas Trump Tower P4220699.jpg|Trump Hotel in 2018\n</gallery>\n\n==DJT restaurant==\nThe DJT restaurant is the flagship full-service restaurant at the property. <ref>{{cite news|last= Friess|first= Steve|url= http://lasvegassun.com/news/2011/apr/27/donald-trumps-political-positions-could-hurt-his-l/|title= Donald Trump's political positions could hurt his Las Vegas business|date= April 27, 2011|newspaper= Las Vegas Sun|accessdate= February 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last= West|first= Jinae|url= http://lasvegassun.com/blogs/culture/2009/jun/26/michelin-bad-economy-means-no-2010-guide-las-vegas/|title= Michelin: Bad economy means no 2010 guide in Las Vegas|date= June 26, 2009|newspaper = Las Vegas Sun|accessdate= February 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Trump International Hotel and Tower (disambiguation)|Trump International Hotel and Tower]]\n* [[List of tallest buildings in Las Vegas]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://www.trumphotels.com/las-vegas/ Trump International Hotel Las Vegas] \u2013 official hotel website\n*[http://www.trumplv.com/ Trump Las Vegas Condominiums] \u2013 official real estate website\n\n{{Las Vegas hotels}}\n{{Las Vegas skyscrapers}}\n{{Las Vegas Strip}}\n{{Trump businesses}}\n\n[[Category:Condo hotels in the United States]]\n[[Category:Skyscraper hotels in Paradise, Nevada]]\n[[Category:Residential skyscrapers in the Las Vegas Valley]]\n[[Category:Hotel buildings completed in 2008]]\n[[Category:Timeshare]]\n[[Category:Assets owned by the Trump Organization]]\n[[Category:Donald Trump real estate]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in Nevada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox building\n| image = Trump International Hotel Las Vegas.jpg\n| caption = Trump International Hotel Las Vegas, January 2017.\n| location = [[Paradise, Nevada]], [[United States]]\n| address = 2000 Fashion Show Drive\n| coordinates = {{coord|36.1296|-115.1727|format=dms|type:landmark_region:US-NV|display=inline,title}}\n| groundbreaking_date = July 12, 2005\n| start_date = November 2005\n| architect = \n| owner = [[Phil Ruffin]], [[Trump Organization]], [[Hilton Grand Vacations]]\n| floor_area = {{convert|185,805|m2|abbr=on}}\n| parking = 550\n| building_type = [[Condo hotel]]\n| hotel_name = Trump International Hotel Las Vegas\n| logo = \n| logo_width = \n| logo_caption = \n| topped_out_date = May 25, 2007\n| opening_date = {{Start date|2008|03|31}}\n| developer = [[Trump Organization]]\n| operator = [[Trump Organization]]\n| number_of_rooms = \n| number_of_suites = 1,282\n| number_of_restaurants = 2\n| floors = 64\n| height = {{convert|622|ft}}\n| website = {{url|trumphotels.com/las-vegas}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\nThe '''Trump International Hotel Las Vegas''' is a 64-story [[Luxury real estate|luxury]] [[hotel]], [[condominium]], and [[timeshare]] located on Fashion Show Drive near [[Las Vegas Boulevard]], just off the [[Las Vegas Strip]] in [[Paradise, Nevada|Paradise]], [[Nevada]], US, named for real estate developer and the 45th and current [[President of the United States]] [[Donald Trump]]. It is located down the street from [[Wynn Las Vegas]], behind the former site of the [[New Frontier Hotel and Casino]] on {{convert|3.46|acre|m2}}, near the [[Fashion Show Mall]], and features both non-residential hotel condominiums and residential [[condominium]]s. The exterior glass is infused with gold.<ref>{{cite news |first=Michael J. |last=Mishak |title=Trump's tower a sore spot on the Strip |date=April 30, 2011 |accessdate=November 11, 2016 |website=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/apr/30/nation/la-na-0430-trump-vegas-20110430}}</ref>\n\nTower 1 opened on March 31, 2008, with 1,282 rooms.<ref name= apr30>{{cite news|last= Mishak|first= Michael J.|url= http://articles.latimes.com/2011/apr/30/nation/la-na-0430-trump-vegas-20110430|title= Trump's tower a sore spot on the Strip|date= April 30, 2011|newspaper= Los Angeles Times|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref> It has two restaurants: DJT, the developer's initials, and a poolside restaurant, H2(eau).<ref name=LATblog033108>Jen Leo, [https://web.archive.org/web/20080426133010/http://travel.latimes.com/daily-deal-blog/?p=1599 Las Vegas Trump Tower opens today], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', March 31, 2008.</ref>  Trump announced that a second, identical tower would be built next to the first tower, but the plan was suspended after the mid-2000s recession. It is [[Las Vegas Valley|Las Vegas's]] tallest residential building at {{convert|622|ft}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trumplv.com/pdfs/fact_sheet.pdf|title=Fact sheet|website=Trumplv.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070703164553/http://www.trumplv.com/pdfs/fact_sheet.pdf|archivedate=2007-07-03}}</ref> In September 2012, the [[Trump Organization]] announced that it sold roughly 300 condominium units in Trump International Hotel Las Vegas to [[Hilton Worldwide]]'s timeshare division, [[Hilton Grand Vacations]].<ref>{{cite web|last= Segall|first= Eli|url= http://m.vegasinc.com/news/2012/sep/06/trump-tower-las-vegas-strip-sells-300-units-timesh/|title= Trump tower on Las Vegas Strip sells some 300 units as timeshares|date= September 6, 2012|website= Vegas Inc}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn April 2002, [[Phil Ruffin]] announced that he had partnered with Donald Trump to build Trump Tower Las Vegas, a $300 million 60-story condominium tower with 300 units and the possibility of a casino, to be constructed on Fashion Show Drive, near Ruffin's [[New Frontier Hotel and Casino]]. Trump had initially approached Ruffin two years earlier about developing a property on or near the Las Vegas Strip. Construction on Trump Tower Las Vegas was to begin in six to seven months, and was expected to last approximately 18 months.<ref>{{cite news|last= Robison|first= Jennifer|url= http://lasvegassun.com/news/2002/apr/23/trump-ruffin-in-lv-luxury-condo-deal/|title= Trump, Ruffin in LV luxury condo deal|date= April 23, 2002|newspaper= [[Las Vegas Sun]]|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref> In August 2003, Ruffin said the tower had been decreased to 43 stories and was expected to cost $272 million.<ref name=nov6>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2003/Nov-06-Thu-2003/business/22527967.html|title=Trump: Only things up in air about Las Vegas plans are where, how big|last=Simpson|first=Jeff|date=November 6, 2003|work=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050131093509/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2003/Nov-06-Thu-2003/business/22527967.html|archive-date=January 31, 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2003, Trump denied that the project had been delayed or that it was suffering from a lack of financing. Trump also said he was considering \"something on a larger scale\" for the project.<ref name=nov6/><ref>{{cite news|last= Benston|first= Liz|url= http://lasvegassun.com/news/2003/nov/06/ruffin-trump-exploring-larger-vegas-condo-complex/|title= Ruffin, Trump exploring larger Vegas condo complex|date= November 6, 2003|newspaper= Las Vegas Sun|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref> In July 2004, Ruffin said the project had been delayed up to that point because of other business ventures, including Trump's reality television show, ''[[The Apprentice (U.S. TV series)|The Apprentice]]''.<ref name= july30>{{cite news|last= Shubinski|first= Jennifer|url= http://lasvegassun.com/news/2004/jul/30/trump-in-new-lv-condo-deal/|title= Trump in new LV condo deal|date= July 30, 2004|newspaper= Las Vegas Sun|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref> That month, Trump and Ruffin announced revised plans for Trump International Hotel and Tower, a $300 million condominium-hotel with over 1,000 units.<ref name= july30/> Although Trump held a Nevada gaming license, he chose not to include a casino on the property.<ref>{{cite news|last= Hirsch|first= Jerry|url= http://articles.latimes.com/2004/jul/30/business/fi-trump30|title= Trump's New Big, Big Idea: Condos on the Vegas Strip|date= July 30, 2004|newspaper= Los Angeles Times|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref> Donald Trump's son [[Eric Trump]] later said, \"We have no problem getting a gaming license, but we wanted to do something different here. We wanted a true luxury resort experience. It's hard to have a high-quality product when you walk into 'ding, ding, ding' and there are people walking around in [[Aloha shirt|Hawaiian shirts]] with big plastic drink mugs.\"<ref name=vegasinc>{{cite web|url=http://vegasinc.com/business/tourism/2013/apr/02/hired-or-fired-how-trump-doing-after-5-years/|title=Hired or fired? How the Trump is doing after five years in Las Vegas|last=Sylvester|first=Ron|date=April 2, 2013|website=VegasInc.com|access-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nRuffin appeared in an October 2004 episode of ''The Apprentice'' to sign a $300 million deal with Trump regarding the project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2004/Oct-31-Sun-2004/business/25115551.html|title=Inside Gaming: Street hints suitors souring on Rio|last=Smith|first=Rod|date=October 31, 2004|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041208192018/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2004/Oct-31-Sun-2004/business/25115551.html|archive-date=December 8, 2004}}</ref> The project was referenced again in the show's [[The Apprentice (U.S. season 2)|second-season]] finale, when winner [[Kelly Perdew]] was offered a job at the property.<ref name=april9/> [[Jack Wishna]], who introduced Trump to Ruffin, was a minority partner in the project.<ref name= apr30/><ref name= july13/> In January 2005, the project was valued at $1 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Jan-21-Fri-2005/business/25705091.html|title=Expert sees upside for high-rise condos|last=Smith|first=Hubble|date=January 21, 2005|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051212012307/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Jan-21-Fri-2005/business/25705091.html|archive-date=December 12, 2005}}</ref> Groundbreaking was initially scheduled for May 2005, with completion expected by the end of 2006.<ref name=april11/> By May 2005, all of the tower's 1,282 condominium units had been reserved by prospective buyers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/May-05-Thu-2005/business/1409613.html|title=Trump condo project reserves all 1,283 units|last=Stutz|first=Howard|date=May 5, 2005|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050507102935/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/May-05-Thu-2005/business/1409613.html|archive-date=May 7, 2005}}</ref>\n\nTrump and Ruffin held a groundbreaking ceremony for the project on July 12, 2005.<ref name= july13>{{cite news|last= Benston|first= Liz|url= http://lasvegassun.com/news/2005/jul/13/trump-the-star-of-the-show-in-condo-resort-groundb/|title= Trump the star of the show in condo resort groundbreaking|date= July 13, 2005|newspaper= Las Vegas Sun|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Jul-12-Tue-2005/business/2469393.html|title=With project's start, Trump's time has come|last=Stutz|first=Howard|date=July 12, 2005|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051118155355/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Jul-12-Tue-2005/business/2469393.html|archive-date=November 18, 2005}}</ref> The ''[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]'' wrote that the event was \"really a [[Ribbon-cutting ceremony|ribbon-cutting]] and photo opportunity\". News programs such as ''[[Access Hollywood]]'' and ''[[Extra (U.S. TV program)|Extra]]'' provided coverage of the event, which was attended by approximately 300 state and local government representatives, as well as [[Carolyn Goodman (politician)|Carolyn Goodman]], [[showgirl]]s, [[Steve Wynn]] and his wife [[Elaine Wynn]], and [[Miss USA 2005]] winner [[Chelsea Cooley]].<ref name= july13/><ref name=lvrjJul13>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Jul-13-Wed-2005/business/2484466.html|title=Living the high life, Trump style|last=Stutz|first=Howard|date=July 13, 2005|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060427032759/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Jul-13-Wed-2005/business/2484466.html|archive-date=April 27, 2006}}</ref>\n\nCondominium units went on sale the same day with the opening of a $3 million temporary sales center at the corner of South Las Vegas Boulevard and Fashion Show Drive, in front of the New Frontier. The building was {{convert|8100|sqft|abbr=on}}, and featured a 10-foot replica of the tower.<ref name= july13/><ref name=april11/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Jun-21-Tue-2005/business/2210922.html|title=Trump International Hotel groundbreaking set for July 12|last=Sutz|first=Howard|date=June 21, 2005|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060427001205/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Jun-21-Tue-2005/business/2210922.html|archive-date=April 27, 2006}}</ref> That month, an [[NBA]] team was in negotiations to purchase an entire floor of the tower, while Trump was considering an alternative version of ''The Apprentice'' that would involve the tower.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Jul-13-Wed-2005/news/26873256.html|title=Team in talks to buy Trump floor |last=Clarke|first=Norm|date=July 13, 2005|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051208014415/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2005/Jul-13-Wed-2005/news/26873256.html|archive-date=December 8, 2005}}</ref> Construction was expected to begin by the end of that summer, and was expected to last 24 to 30 months.<ref name=lvrjJul13/>\n\nConstruction began in November 2005, when the building's foundation was poured.<ref name= may27>{{cite news|url= http://www.reviewjournal.com/real-estate/trump-celebrates-project|title= Trump celebrates project|date= May 27, 2007|newspaper = Las Vegas Review-Journal|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref> After the completion of a 36,000-square-foot recreational deck in March 2006, an average of 800 workers constructed one new floor for the tower approximately every six days.<ref name= may27/> The tower was [[topping out|topped out]] on May 25, 2007.<ref name= may27/> The project was constructed at a cost of $500 million,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2006/Oct-15-Sun-2006/business/9667092.html|title=The Next Wave|last=Stutz|first=Howard|date=October 15, 2006|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061201164752/http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2006/Oct-15-Sun-2006/business/9667092.html|archive-date=December 1, 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/site-work-under-way-windmill-lane-plaza|title=Site work under way for Windmill Lane Plaza|date=May 28, 2007|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|access-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref> on {{convert|3|acres|abbr=on}} of land that was part of the rear parking lot for the New Frontier.<ref name= july13/> The project was designed by [[Joel Bergman|Bergman, Walls & Associates]] and built by [[Perini Building Company]].<ref name= may27/>\n\nTrump Hotel Las Vegas opened on March 31, 2008. An opening ceremony was held by Trump and Ruffin on April 11, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://mix941fm.cbslocal.com/2011/07/05/recap-the-good-years-with-mayor-oscar-goodman/trump-international-hotel-tower-las-vegas-opening-ceremony/|title= Trump International Hotel & Tower Las Vegas - Opening Ceremony|publisher= CBS| date= July 5, 2011|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref> By October 2008, only 21 percent of condo unit sales had closed, as potential buyers had trouble securing mortgages.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lvrj.com/business/30934179.html|title=Credit squeeze hits high-rises|last=Knightly|first=Arnold M.|date=October 14, 2008|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081015141654/http://www.lvrj.com/business/30934179.html|archive-date=October 15, 2008}}</ref> {{as of|2013}}, Eric Trump oversees operations at the tower.<ref name=vegasinc/>\n\nOn December 4\u20135, 2015, employees voted in favor of unionizing the hotel property. It was organized by the Bartenders Union and the [[Culinary Workers Union]] and supervised by the [[National Labor Relations Board]] (NLRB) under the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Stutz|first=Howard|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/culinary-calls-contract-talks-after-trump-workers-vote-union|title=Culinary calls for contract talks after Trump workers vote for union|date=December 7, 2015|newspaper=[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]|accessdate=December 7, 2015}}</ref> Donald Trump owns a penthouse on the 61st floor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/trump-hotel-executive-uses-personalized-care-build-customer-base|title=Trump hotel executive uses personalized care to build customer base|last=|first=|date=June 30, 2008|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|access-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Second tower===\nBy April 2005, a second, identical 64-story tower was being planned.<ref name= april11>{{cite web|url= http://www.adweek.com/news/advertising/it-takes-2-gearys-sell-trump-towers-78878|last= Schmelzer|first= Randi|title= It Takes 2 Gearys to Sell Trump Towers|work= Adweek|date= April 11, 2005|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref> Sales of the second tower were planned to begin by the end of 2005, with a 35 percent increase in prices from the first tower.<ref name=lvrjJul13/> In November 2005, the second tower was planned to open sometime in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last=Benston|first= Liz|url= http://lasvegassun.com/news/2005/nov/20/north-strip-brink-of-a-boom/|title= North Strip: Brink of a boom?|date= November 20, 2005|newspaper= Las Vegas Sun|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2007, the second tower was the subject of an episode of ''The Apprentice'' in which the show's candidates were tasked with creating a marketing program for the new tower.<ref name=april9>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/tower-pitch-goes-prime-time|title=Tower Pitch Goes Prime Time|last=|first=|date=April 9, 2007|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|access-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.reviewjournal.com/real-estate/trump-announces-second-tower|title= Trump announces second tower|date= May 6, 2007|newspaper = Las Vegas Review-Journal|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref> Condo units for the tower went on sale the next day.<ref name=april9/><ref name= may27/> Trump said the tower would be nearly identical to the first tower, and would also include 1,282 units.<ref name=april9/> Because of rising construction expenses, the second tower was expected to cost $625 million, which would have brought the total cost of Trump International Hotel and Tower to $1.1 billion.<ref name=april9/> This number was later reported to be $1.2 billion in February 2008, at which point the second tower was expected to begin construction at the end of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/business/opening-slated-trump-condo-hotel|title=Opening slated for Trump condo-hotel|date=February 5, 2008|work=Las Vegas Review-Journal|access-date=May 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2008, Trump said he had not decided on a start date for the second tower, choosing to wait until all sales had closed on the first tower's rooms. At that time, reservations were still being accepted for the second tower's units.<ref>{{cite news|last= Stutz|first= Howard|url= http://www.reviewjournal.com/inside-gaming/trumps-second-tower-may-wait|title= Trump's second tower may wait|date= April 6, 2008|newspaper= Las Vegas Review-Journal|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref> The second tower was ultimately put on hold because of bad credit markets.<ref name= August1/> In August 2015, Eric Trump spoke of the potential for the second tower: \"I think in time it's a very good possibility.\"<ref name= August1>{{cite news|last = Botkin|first= Ben|url= http://www.reviewjournal.com/politics/elections/trump-has-piece-las-vegas|title= Trump has a piece of Las Vegas|date= August 1, 2015|newspaper= Las Vegas Review-Journal|accessdate= February 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Lobby Trump International Hotel Las Vegas (38532499500).jpg|Lobby\nFile:Lobby Trump International Hotel Las Vegas (38532498610).jpg